description: From Middle English cheste, chiste, from Old English ċest, ċist (“chest, casket; coffin; rush basket; box”), from Proto-West Germanic *kistu (“chest, box”), from Latin cista (“chest, box”), from Ancient Greek κίστη (kístē, “chest, box, basket, hamper”), from Proto-Indo-European *kisteh₂ (“woven container”).
Germanic cognates include Scots kist (“chest, box, trunk, coffer”), West Frisian kiste (“box, chest”), Dutch kist (“box, case, chest, coffin”), German Kiste (“box, crate, case, chest”).

entries.meaning: A box, now usually a large strong box with a secure convex lid.
examples: The clothes are kept in a chest.

entries.meaning: The place in which public money is kept; a treasury.
examples: You can take the money from the chest.

entries.meaning: (anatomy) The portion of the front of the human body from the base of the neck to the top of the abdomen; the thorax. Also the analogous area in other animals.
examples: She had a sudden pain in her chest.

entries.meaning: A hit or blow made with one's chest.
examples: He scored with a chest into the goal.

verbs.description: chest (third-person singular simple present chests, present participle chesting, simple past and past participle chested)

entries.meaning: To hit with one's chest (front of one's body)
(transitive, obsolete) To place in a coffin.

description: From Middle English chest, cheste, cheeste, cheaste, from Old English ċēast, ċēas (“strife, quarrel, quarrelling, contention, murmuring, sedition, scandal; reproof”). Related to Old Frisian kāse (“strife, contention”), Old Saxon caest (“quarrel, dispute”), Old High German kōsa (“speech, story, account”).
